And I think finally you would use this function: `python/mxnet/model.score`, link is [here](https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/python/mxnet/model.py#L676). If so, you don't have to worry about that, because `reset=True` by default.
If you are not using this function, I would say it would be no harm to do `reset()` unless you need some online validation info.

@haimeh Sorry for the late reply. You can get the information from the python API document: http://mxnet.io/api/python/symbol.html#mxnet.symbol.Convolution

In 3D convolution, the shape of input should be `(batch_size, channel, depth, height, width)`.

You can try to change `dim(train.array) <- c(3,3,5,3000)` to `dim(train.array) <- c(3,3,5,1,3000)`.

@ashwin-cognitiv I haven't tried it yet, as I always call this function `mod.score(val_iter, val_metrics, epoch=e)` (the link I attached above).

And followed source code from [here](https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/python/mxnet/metric.py#L106-L109), what I would sugget is simply print the `num_inst` and `sum_metrics` to see if that's what you want.

BTW. My understanding of `self.num_inst` is the sample number that you want to evaluate on one data pass, which means you should reset it after each data pass. And if you are using the `mod.score()` function, it will create new [eval metrics](https://github.com/dmlc/mxnet/blob/master/python/mxnet/model.py#L693-L694), so you don't have to reset the metric.

